photo.description: Seville, the Giralda (tower) of the Catedral de Santa Maria de la Sede The Giralda is a former minaret that was converted to a bell tower for the Cathedral of Seville. The tower is 104.5 m in height. The tower was begun under the architect Ahmad Ben Baso in 1184. The tower was completed March 10, 1198 with the installation of copper spheres on the tower's top. (From Wikipedia, en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giralda)

photo.description: The Cathedral of Saint Mary of the See (Spanish: Catedral de Santa María de la Sede), better known as Seville Cathedral, is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Seville (Andalusia, Spain). It is the largest Gothic cathedral and the third-largest church in the world. After its completion in the early 16th century, Seville Cathedral supplanted Hagia Sophia as the largest cathedral in the world, a title the Byzantine church had held for nearly a thousand years. The cathedral also serves as the burial site of Christopher Columbus. The Archbishop's Palace is located on the northeastern side of the cathedral. Seville Cathedral. (2012, April 4). In Wikipedia, The Free Encyclopedia. Retrieved 22:38, April 14, 2012, from en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Seville_Cathedral&...
